ce:section.ce:para:
To put emphasis on our current findings and substantiate the practical application of N‒GQD in human healthcare, we carried out the detection of Gly in commercial milk samples. The commercial milk samples such as cow and soya milk are purchased from shops in the vicinity that are diluted with deionized water (50-fold), spiked with a known concentration of Gly (200.0 × 10−9 M), and examined with fluorescence technique. The fluorescence emission intensities of N‒GQD (1.0 × 10−6 M) progressively decreased upon sequential addition of Gly spiked milk samples (100.0 × 10−9 M) (Fig. 10
                     ), which is in good homogeneity with earlier non-spiked Gly sample analysis (Fig. 6), and the calculated LoD (56.99 × 10−12 M for spiked cow milk, and 55.27 × 10−12 M for spiked soya milk; Fig. SI15 and SI16, respectively) and quantitative recoveries are found to be in the range from ∼102 to 107% (Table 1
                     ) [58,59]. The above results indicate that the other ingredients in real milk samples did not cause any severe interference in the detection of Gly. Therefore, we recommend that the detection of Gly in real samples in picomolar concentration is attainable by using excitation-independent and fluorescence-reversible N‒GQDs.
